  "text": "HbCO: [CITATION_1] reported that the nonsmokers' HbCO is Ͻ2.0%, depending upon environmental pollutants, while the heavy smoker (Նone pack/day) has values Ͼ4.0%. The 5.5% level in smokers in the present study is greater than the 4.3% level, previously shown to be the minimal level affecting VO 2 max [CITATION_2] . [CITATION_3] reported a 9% reduction in VO 2 max of smokers with a 7% elevation in HbCO. This suggests that a portion of the 9% lower VO 2 max (L/min) in smokers in the present study can be attributed to CO binding with Hb and a reduction in oxygen carrying capacity. At maximal work levels 90% of the oxygen carrying capacity may be needed [CITATION_4] . The 5% reduction in this capacity by CO means the muscles' maximal aerobic metabolism is reduced unless the cardiac output is further increased. The similarity of the exercise HR values in the nonsmokers and smokers at equivalent stress levels (Fig. 2) suggests that the cardiovascular system was fully and equally taxed in both groups in terms of stroke volume. This indicates that the arteriovenous difference was smaller and the O 2 extraction reduced in smokers. The %fat was significantly 166 Smoking and Cardiorespiratory Responses ",
